ground_truth:
Design of a balanced scorecard is about the identification of a small number of financial and non-financial measures and attaching targets to them, so that when they are reviewed it is possible to determine whether current performance 'meets expectations'. This is illustrated by the four steps required to design a balanced scorecard included in Kaplan & Norton's writing on the subject in the late 1990s:

- Translating the vision into operational goals;
- Communicating the vision and link it to individual performance;
- Business planning; index setting
- Feedback and learning, and adjusting the strategy accordingly.
